fields.title: What is resistor?
fields.tags: what is resistor,how resistor works,ohms law,why we use resistor,basics of electronics
fields.body:
A resistor is an electronic component.It is use to pass limit current in the circuit.it is made of special material resistance to flow of electricity.Resistor are use to various purpose like in electronic circuits such as controlling the amount of current or voltage in electronic circuit,dividing voltages and many other application. They comes in various shapes,sizes and color with difference resistance values.The resistance is measured in ohms (Ω).The resister are fundamental electrical component used to in analog and  digital circuits.

How resistor works?

Resistor are create friction for electrons to flowing through a electric circuit.The resistor  converts some of electric energy into heat,which is why when we touch resistor can feel warm is in use.

Material : Resistor are made form materials that conducting electricity poorly.These materials have high resistance,which create the harder to flow electron in resistor.The resistor made of material such as :-Carbon,Zinc etc.

Friction and Flow : The electrons try to push through in the resistor.The electrons collide to the atoms in the resistor.This collision lost some of there energy,reducing the current that flow in the resister.

Heat Generation : This collision converts electrical energy to heat.So,the    temperature of resistor is more than to before and we can feel that resistor is warm.The amount of heat is depend on amount of voltage and resistance value of resistor.

Types of resistor:

There are two types main of resistor are as:-    

1.Fixed resistor
2.Variable resistor

1.Fixed resistor: These types of resistor have specific resistance value cannot be adjusted.These type of resistor come in various types.Main types of resistor such as carbon film,metal film,wirewound and various other types.

Carbon composition: This types of resistor made of mixture carbon and ceremic,they expensive and widely use.

Metal film: This is made of deposition a thin film of metal on a ceremic rode,They are more stability and accuracy than to carbon film resistor.

Wire wound: This types of resistor constructed by widing a resistance wire,typically it is made if nicrome and other alloy,around an ceremic or fibreglass core.

2.Variable resistor: This types of resistor are also kown as potentiomter and rheostats,this types of are can adjustable resistance value.Various types of resistor such as potentiometer,rheostats,Light-Depented Resistor and other types.

Potentiometer: This types of resistor have three terminals 5v,output and ground.These resistor are used as voltage divider or adjusting the value of reisistance.

Rheostats: These types of resistor have two-terminals variable used to control current in circuit.

Light-Depented Resistor(LDR’s): These types of resisitor also known as photoresistor.These types of resisotor change their resistance based on the intensity of light that falling on them.They are use in ligth-sesitive application like street lights,light meters,control exposure of camera and other various electrical application.

 

 OHM’s Law:

OHM’s law describe reletion between resistance,voltage,current is an  electrical circuit

V=I×R

Where:
V represents voltage, measured in volts (V).
I represents current, measured in amperes (A).
R represents resistance, measured in ohms (Ω).
To determine the current:

I=V/R

To determine the resistance:

R=V/I

fields.title: How black holes are form?
fields.tags: how blackhole are form,what is star,how a massive star die.
fields.body:
A black hole is a region in space where gravity is so intense that it forms an area with an escape velocity greater than the speed of light. As a result, nothing, not even light itself, can escape from within the black hole's boundary, known as the event horizon. The immense gravitational force of a black hole is caused by an extremely dense mass packed into a tiny volume, known as a singularity at the center. Black holes can come in various sizes, from small stellar-mass black holes formed from the collapse of massive stars to supermassive black holes found at the centers of galaxies, containing millions or even billions of times the mass of our Sun.


What is star?

Star is body of hot,glowing gas that are born in nebulae.They vary enormously in size,mass,and temperature:diameter range from about 450 smaller to 1000 bigger that that of the Sun;masses range from about a twentieth to over 50 solar masses;and surface temperature range form about 3000 degree celcius to over 50000 degree celcius.

 


Life time of massive star:

Massive stars have at least three times that of the Sun,and some stars are as massive as about 50 Suns.A massive star evolves in a similar way to a small stars until it reaches the main sequence stage.During its  life as a main sequence star, it shines steadily until the hydrogen in its core has fused to form helium.This process takes billion of years in a small star,but only millions of years in a massive star. A massive star then becomes a red supergaint,which initially consist of helium core sorrounded by outer layers of cooling,expanding gas over the next few million years a series of nuclear reaction from differrent element in shells around an iron core eventually collapse in less than  second causing massive explosion called supernova,In which a shock waves blows away the outer layer of the star.Supernova shine brighter  than an entire galaxy for a short time.Sometimes the core survives   the supernova explosion.If the surviving core is between about one and half and three solar masses,it contracts  to became tiny dense Neutron star.If the core is greater than three solar masses,it contracts  to became  a “black hole”.

fields.title: Magnetic properties of substances
fields.tags: What are Magnetic properties of substance?,what is diamagnetic, paramagnetic and ferromagnetic substances?,
fields.body:
Every substance is made of atoms .Each atom has electrons, which revolve around the nucleus of the atom. Like planets, electrons have also two types of rotations, orbital motion and spin. So, each electron behaves as a magnetic dipole and has magnetic moment.

This molecular theory describes the magnetic behaviour of substances.

On the basis of molecular theory magnetic substances are two types

 1. Non-magnetic substances 

 2. Magnetic substance

Non-Magnetic Substance

Those substance whose resultant magnetic moment (magnitude and directions) of molecular electron cancel each other and becomes zero. So that the magnetic property do not arise in those molecules of substance are called non magnetic substance.

Example: copper, aluminium, sodium etc. 

Magnetic Substance 

Some substance do not cancel their magnetic moment of atomic electrons so that the resultant magnetic moment of the molecules does not become zero and the molecule behaves as a magnetic dipole, which is known as molecular magnet and substance are called magnetic substance.

Example: iron, Cobalt, nickel etc. 

Molecular Properties of Magnetic Substances

✓ Molecular theory of magnetism was first introduced by German scientist Weber.

✓ According to Weber magnetism is the molecular property of magnetic substances.

✓ According to scientist Ewing, in any magnetic substance the molecular magnets form closed chains and due to no free poles of their molecule magnets they do not so magnetic property.

✓ Due to magnetisation this closed chains opens up and molecular magnets get arranged in series. In the presence of opposite pole in the ends. They show magnetic property 

✓ Middle portion of the magnet have no free poles. So no magnetism is felt there.

✓ There are many magnetic phenomena in magnetic substances

1. Magnetic induction 

2. Magnetization by rubbing 

3. Magnetic saturation

4. Magnetostriction

5. Demagnetisation by rough handling

6. Heat produced by rapid magnetization and demonetization

Classification of Substances

On the behaviour of substances in external magnetic field, Michael Faraday divided all substances into three categories:

1. Diamagnetic substances 

2. Paramagnetic substances and 

3. Ferromagnetic substances

Diamagnetic Substance 

Those substances, which are repelled feebly by strong magnets are known as diamagnetic substances.

 Example: zinc, copper, silver, gold, lead,Mercury etc.

Paramagnetic Substance 

The substances which are attracted feebly by a strong magnet are known as paramagnetic substances.

Example: aluminium, potassium, platinum, sodium, tin, manganese etc.

Ferromagnetic Substance 

The substances iron (Fe), nickel(Ni), Cobalt(Co), godolinium(Gd), dysprosium(Dy) and alloy like Steel etc. are attracted strongly by magnet even if inducing magnetic field is removed, these substances can retains induced magnetism are known as ferromagnetic substances.

Magnetic Retentivity 

When a magnetic substance is placed in a magnetic field the substance acquires magnetism due to magnetic induction this magnetism does not vanish completely even after the remove of magnetic field.

This property of ferromagnetic substances to retain some magnetism in it even after the withdrawal of the magnetising field is called magnetic retentivity of that substance.

Coercivity 

The property of which a magnetic substances retain induced magnetism even if used roughly is called coercivity of that material.

fields.title: what is programming?
fields.tags: what is programming, what is coding, software devlopment,programming,coding,software development
fields.body:
We communicate to any person for share informations with a common languages like hindi, english, marathi , bangali, oddisi , french ,etc . But if we try to talk with computer from this languages it cannot understand our words.The computer only understand 0 and 1 which means binaries.But we cannot talk in binaries it too difficult to use. Just example I say "01001000 01100101 01101100 01101100 01101111 00100000 01100010 01110010 01101111 " to you. It means "hello bro". Therefore , we use a specific language called Programming language which ease the communicate with computer.

Simply, programming language is a easiest way for programmers to communicate with computers. Programming languages consist of a set of rules that allows string values to be compile the codes into machine code or Binary.

 

There are Hundreds of programming languges in the world. Some famous are:

  1. Javascript
  2. Python
  3. Go
  4. Java
  5. Kotlin
  6. PHP
  7. C#
  8. R
  9. C++
  10. C language
  11. Matlab
  12. TypeScript
  13. Scala
  14. SQL
  15. HTML
  16. CSS

 

There are two types of Programming languages:

  1. High Level language (HLL)
  2. Low Level Language (LLL)

 

Low Level language(LLL)

These programming languages are more difficult to understand. It is designed to operate and handle the entire instruction set of a computer system directly which are generally used to write the system software.

There are two low level language :

1. Machine Language
2. Assembly Language

 

Machine Language : It is the only language understand by the computers. Sometimes, it referred to as machine code or object code or binary language. It is a collection of binary digits ( 0 or 1 ) or bits that the computer understands and interprets to do tasks.

Assembly Language : It is a low level programming language which is used as an structured commands as substitutions for numbers. It is easier to to read as human as compare to binary.

 


High level language(HLL)

It is an advanced type of computer programming language which is no limited to only one computer, it is designed for performed a specific job or task. The main advantage of the HLL is they are vary easier to read, write and understand.

example: Javascript, Python,Go, Java, Kotlin, C ,C++, etc.

fields.title: What is Kinetic Theory of Gases?
fields.tags: What is Kinetic Theory of Gases?, pressure of gas, assumptions or Postulates of Kinetic Theory of gases
fields.body:
Kinetic theory of gases is based on the assumptions of internal molecular behaviour of gases. 

In the molecular model, the molecules of gases are in motion and show internal microscopic properties like velocity, intermolecular distance, intermolecular forces etc.

Molecular motion is the basic concept of Kinetic theory of gases, which has many evidences -

  •   Diffusion 
  •   Vaporisation of liquid 
  •  Expansion of gas
  •  Brownian motion

# Basic assumptions (Postulates) of Kinetic Theory of Gases :

1. A gas is a composition of a large number of identical molecules.(Different molecule for different gases).

2. Every gas molecule behaves as a point mass.

3. The molecules are in continuous and random motion in all possible directions. 

4. During random motion, the molecules collide with each other and the walls of container.

5. Potential energy of a molecule of a gas is negligible and total energy is a kinetic energy only. 

6. Every collision between the molecules is instantaneous mens time of collision is negligible. 

7. After collision molecules move with uniform velocity in free path means straight line.

#Note-

* The mass of gas is the sum of the masses of its constituent molecules.

* The volume of gas is the inner volume of the gas container.

Hence, 

A gas that follows the properties of given assumptions of kinetic theory of gases is called ideal gas or perfect gas. 

The Real gases show some deviation from this properties.

# Pressure of a perfect gas

The pressure of a gas is the force exerted normally by the gas molecule on unit area of the walls of its container. 

Which is derived as

                         P=1/3 ρc2

     Where,  ρ and c are density and rms velocity of  the gas respectively.​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​

# Interpretation of Temperature 

When a gas absorbs heat it's temperature increases and converts its heat energy into kinetic energy of a gas.

fields.title: How thunderstorm form?
fields.tags: thunderstorm,how thunderstorm form,what is hail stones,how hail stones produce,what is cumulonimbus clouds,temperture of sorrounding when thunder stroke create,how flash floods caused due to thunder storm
fields.body:
A violent disturbance in the atmosphere is called storm. There are many different types of storms. Some arise over land, others develop over seas. Some are accompanied by thunder, lightning and heavy rain. Others are dry dust storms. We will discuss about three broad types of storms- thunderstorms, tornadoes and cyclones. In this topic we will only discuss with thunderstorms.

 

Thunderstorm Thunderstorms develop from cumulonimbus clouds. When there is a rapid upward rush of warm air from very hot areas on the ground and a rapid downward movement of cool air around the warm air, these clouds are formed. The top of a cumulonimbus cloud may reach the bottom of the stratosphere. Inside the clouds, the warm and moist air rapidly rises up. In doing so the water vapour in it rapidly condenses to form tiny droplets of water, which freeze to form small particles of ice. During the condensation and freezing, a large amount of energy is released. This heat energy further pushes up the air at a higher speed. The water and ice particles rub against each other in rapidly rising air. This builds up a negative electric charge in the clouds. This electric charge is then released by the clouds by the stroke of lightning.

The lightning heats the surrounding air to a temperature of 30,000°C. The heat released by lightning makes the air expand very-very fast, even faster than sound. This in turn produces a crash of thunder similar to the sound produced by supersonic aeroplanes. The thunderstorms are accompanied by heavy rains and high speed wind which can damage weak buildings, uproot trees, submerge crops and can cause flash floods.

Sometimes ice crystals falling through a thunderstorm are caught and tossed back up by an updraft of warm air. In the process, water droplets freeze on to the crystals and make them bigger. The crystals may bounce up and down several times and get so big and heavy and fall to the ground. This precipitation is called hail and the crystals are called hailstones.

fields.title: Faraday's Experiment for Electromagnet
fields.tags: Faraday's Experiment,electromagnet,electromagnetic induction,law of magnet,bar magnet, what is electromagnet,
fields.body:
Faraday took a solenoid and he connected its two ends by a galvanometer. When the north pole of a magnet was moved towards the coil rapidly, the galvanometer needle deflected. Deflection of the needle indicated the presence of current in the circuit.

If the magnet is held stationary near the solenoid, the galvanometer's needle rests at zero. It means no deflection is shown or the absence of flow of electric current in the circuit. When the north pole of the magnet was moved away from the solenoid, the galvanometer again showed deflection but now this moment was in the opposite direction.

This experiment was again repeated but at this moment, the south pole of the magnet moved towards and away from the solenoid and Faraday observed the deflection in the galvanometer needle once again. After performing this experiment he concluded that whenever magnetic lines of force associated with a coil are changed, an electric current is induced in the coil. This process termed as electromagnetic induction.

It has also been found that if we increase strength of magnet or the number of turns in coil, the magnitude of the induced current increases. If the magnet is kept stationary and the coil is moved towards or away from the magnet, again an induced electric current is in the the coil. 

Electromagnet

Electricity has magnetic effect which is used to prepare electromagnets.when electricity pass through a conductor,it bahaves like a magnet and is called an electromagnet.

Uses of electromagnet:

  1. Electromagnets are very strong temporary magnets when the current is to passed through them and get demagnetized as soon as the current is switched off.

  2. The strength of an electromagnets depends upon the current in the coil and it also depends upon the type of bar used.
  3. These magnets can be made in different sizes and shapes depending on their use.

Strength of electromagnets depends upon the following factors:

  • The number of turns of copper wire wound on the soft iron bar or iron needle.
  • The strength of current flowing through the wire.

fields.title: What is Software?
fields.tags: What is Software?, what is computer software?, what is system software?, what is application software?, what is bios?, what is loader?, software, application
fields.body:
A software is an interface between the user and computer hardware which is created by collection of computer programs and related data, it is also responsible for controlling, integrating and managing the hardware components of a computer system for a specific task.

There are two main categories of software-

1. System software and  

2. Application software 

System Software 

System software provides the interface between the user and components of the computer .It Consists of several programs which are directly responsible for controlling and managing the individual hardware component of a computer system.

There are many types of software systems-

  • Operating System
  • Device Drivers
  • Language Translator
  • Loader
  • BIOS
What are device drivers?
Device driver is the system software, which objective is to make a device functional and act as an interface between the device and the user.
Every device has a driver program. 

 

What is language translator?
Language translator is also a system software which convert the programming language into machine language.
Ex. Assembler compiler and interpreter. 

 

What is loader?
Loader is also a kind of system software which function is to load executable programs into the main memory.
It is a part of operating system that brings an executable file from hard disc into the memory and starts execution process.

 

What is BIOS?
BIOS means the basic input output system which is a system software, it control various electronic components within the main computer system, its function is to initialise system devices like RAM, hard disc, video display to start the computer system.

 

Application Software 

Those softwares which are designed especially for users to perform single or multiple task and enable the user to interact with the computer are called application software.

This programs do the real work for users

There are also two types of application software-

 1. General Purpose Software 

Those software which are used to do simple computer tasks.

Ex. Microsoft word, Microsoft Excel, Microsoft PowerPoint, Microsoft access, my SQL ,Adobe Photoshop, VLC media player etc.

2. Specific Purpose Software

This softwares are designed to perform specific task.

Ex. Accounting software, Billing software, Reservation software, Hotel Management system etc.

fields.title: How to apply for residential certificate in Bihar?
fields.tags: How to apply residential certificate in Bihar?, Bihar residential certificate, certificate, how to apply certificate in Bihar?
fields.body:
Government of Bihar has started a new portal to apply residential certificate online. 

Before apply you need to prepare an identity document from any these like Aadhar card, voter ID card, pan card or driving licence.

If you are a permanent resident then you need other document like electricity bill, PMC tax bill or ration card.

During applying of residential certificate you may verify Aadhar Card authentication.It's not mandatory.

You should prepare a combined PDF of two document one for identity and other for residence proof to annexure during the applying process.

You will also need a self attested JPG photo image of applicant.

Steps 

1. Please visit the website of given link

https://serviceonline.bihar.gov.in

2. Go to RTPS services in General Administrative Department.

3. Then you have to click on resident certificate of Block level means for revenue officer certificated 

4. Fill the all mandatory information in the application and attached self attested image of Applicant.

5. You may verify Aadhar authentication by OTP it's not mandatory. 

6. After proceed attached document combined PDF format of identity and residential proof and finally submit. 

You can download application receipt by clicking on export button in PDF format.

So at the given service date you can download your certificate at the same website on the citizen section download certificate.

Through the same process you can also apply for caste certificate and income certificate.

fields.title: How to apply for caste certificate in Bihar?
fields.tags: How to apply for class certificate in Bihar?, how to apply for caste certificate?, caste certificate, Bihar
fields.body:
Caste certificate is a vary essential certificate for those who has been studying in school or preparing for competitive examination.

Government of Bihar has started a new portal to apply caste certificate online. 

Before apply you need to prepare an identity document from any of these like Aadhar card, voter ID card, school ID card, pan card or driving licence.

During applying of caste certificate you may verify Aadhar Card authentication. It's not mandatory.

You must know your caste category, your caste name and sub-caste name.

You will also need a self attested JPG photo image of applicant.

Steps-

1. Please visit the website of this link

     https://serviceonline.bihar.gov.in

2. Go to RTPS services in General Administrative Department

3. Then you have to click caste certificate on Block level means for revenue officer certificated 

4. Fill the all mandatory information in the application and attached self attested image of Applicant.

5. Please fill your caste category, caste name and sub-caste name correctly otherwise your application could cancel.

6. You may verify Aadhar authentication by OTP it's not mandatory. 

7. After proceed attached document PDF format of identity card and finally submit. 

You can download application receipt by clicking on export button in PDF format.

So at the given service date you can download your certificate at the same website on the citizen section download certificate.

Through the same process you can also apply for residential certificate and income certificate.

fields.title: What is Coriolis Effect?
fields.tags: coriolis effect,what is coriolis effect,hurricane,what is hurricane,how hurricane are form,ocean current,winds
fields.body:
The Coriolis effect plays role in the formation and movement of hurricanes.We will only discuss only about how hurricanes forms and his movement.

Coriolis effect

Unequal heating of the earth's surface forms large global wind system.The sun is almost directly over head for most of the year in the areas near the equator and heat the earth's surface rapidly.The polar regions receive slanting rays from sun.So,the temperature in the polar regions are lower than those in areas near the equator.At the poles ,the cooler air sinks and moves towards the equator.This movement produces global pattern of air circulation.The winds in the northern hemisphere curve to the right as they move.In the southern hemisphere winds curve to the left.This effect is called the coriolis effect.

Cyclones and Hurricanes

hurrianes are the greatest storms on the earth.The word "hurricane" is used in USA and west indies to describe these storms.In China,these stare called typhoons.In australia,the cylones are known as Willy Willy and in the Indian ocean ,they are called cyclones.They form in early fall over the warm tropical waters of Atlantic just north of the equator.At the time,ocean surface temperature is highest.The warm air heats the air above it and creates updrafts of air currents.In the Northern hemisphere,this creates a swirling  counter clockwise movement of air around the low-pressure centre ,called a tropical cyclone. In the  Southern Hemisphere,the movement of air is clockwise.

As time passes,more and more warm air may be drawn up through the centre.As the air rises is spreads out,cools and swirls down and back into cyclone.The air moves fasteras rising warrm air adds energy.When the winds speed reaches about 117 kilometres per hour,the storm is considered as a hurricane.

The air of several hundreds square kilometres are covered by a hurrricane.It can bring  heavy rain which leads to floods ,high winds and storms surgase.Its centre is usually calm and cloudless.This calm centre is usually calm and cloudless.This calm centre is the eye of the storm.Around the eye fierce  wind blow. Hurricanes are not as strong as tornadoes.but,a hurricane is so large ,it packs enormous energy that can damage over a wide area.

fields.title: what is  pyramid?
fields.tags: what is a mummy?, what is pyramid?, what is the reason to build a pyramid?
fields.body:
A mummy is a dead body of human  and other living being organism that had been preserved. In ancient time ,egyptian sought to preserve the soul after died ,then they found out the soul never corpse return to.The pharoah (the ancient king of egypt),their corpse was mummified in the coffin on which spells were inscribed for ward off the evil and had been taken in the pyramid. The poor peoples buried in the sand which inhibited  decay.

What is Pyramid?

The pyramid is ancient building that was built by the pharoahs.It is estimated that the great pyramid of giza was build in the year 2560 BC by pharoah khufu(the monarch of ancient egypt).It was the largest single building to that time.There are 118 pyramids but these are broken by the whether condition only three pyramids are well nows a days. This pyramids are located in the bank of the river Nile.

The three pyramids :

1.The great pyramid of Giza:    It is the largest pyramid that was built by the pharoah Khufu.
2.The pyramid of khafre:      It is the secong largert pyramid that build by the khufu's son khafre.
3.The great pyramid of Menkawe:   It is the third largest phyramid that built by the Khafre's son menkawe.

What the reason of built?

They were built as a tomb.The pharaohs are buried inside the pyramid. The ancient Egyptian believed in the after death .They beleived that the life does not end after died .After the died, the soul of the person travels to the underworld . Where it is then judged by the God. Those who lived a life of goodness who is immoraral in the after life.For this after life, the pharoahs built the  tomb and a large amount of grains tresures, clothes ,furniture,jewellaries taken in the tomb.They think, It would used in the after life and after died these body  was mummified in the pyramid.

fields.title: What is the cell ?
fields.tags: What is the cell?, define the cell?, what is tissue?, what is cytoplasm?, what is nucleus?, what is eukaryotic cell and prokaryotic cell?
fields.body:
A cell is the basic structural unit of an organ or a living organism which perform special basic function.

The cell was discovered by Robert Hooke in 1665 by observing a slice of cork through a simple microscope.Cork is a part of the bark of a tree. 

Characteristics of a cell 

Different living organisms have different shape, size and numbers of cells.Any living organisms have millions and billions of cells.

Generally cells are round, spherical or elongated in shape and some are spindle in shape.

The smallest cell is in bacteria and the largest cell is the egg of an ostrich.

  • The single cell organisms are unicellular.

            Ex. Amoeba, Paramecium 

  • Those organisms who are made up of more than one cell are called multicellular.

             Ex. Animal and Human

A tissue is a group of similar cells performing a specific function. 

Parts of the cell 

Cell membrane  

The cell membrane is the outer layer of the cell in which cytoplasm and nucleus are inclosed. It separates the cells from one another and from the surrounding medium.

It is also known as plasma membrane. 

The cell wall is the additional layer which surround the cell membrane in plants for protection.

Cytoplasm

Cytoplasm is a jelly like substance which is present between the cell membrane and the nucleus in which various other component means organelles are present like mitochondria ,ribosomes etc.

Neucleus

Nucleus is the important component of living cells which is generally spherical and located in the centre of the cell.

Nucleus contains threat like structure called chromosomes which carry genes and help in inheritance.

Nucleus is separated from the cytoplasm by a membrane called the nuclear membrane.

According to nuclear membrane there are two types of cell 

Prokaryotic cells

Those cells having nuclear material without nuclear membrane called prokaryotic cell. 

Ex. Bacteria and blue green algae. 

Eukaryotic cells 

Those cells having well organised nucleus with a nuclear membrane called eukaryotic cells. 

Ex. Animal and human

Protoplasm
Protoplasm is the living substance of the cell which includes the cytoplasm and the nucleus.
Protoplasm = Cytoplasm + Nucleus 

 

# Note -
Plant cells have Cell Wall in the outside layer to protect itself from surrounding. While animal cells does not have cell wall.

fields.title: What is Machine Learning ?
fields.tags: What is machine learning?, machine learning, artificial intelligence, machine learning algorithms, types of machine learnings
fields.body:
Machine learning is an advance transformative field of artificial intelligence that empowers computers to learn and improve from experiences without writing any explicit programs.

What is traditional programming vs machine learning?

In traditional programming, Developers write specific codes with rules and logics for the computer to perform a task, but in machine learning algorithm it enables system to automatically learn patterns and make intelligent decision based on data.

Machine learning is an evolving field by which we can use it in the problem solving and decision making.

There are many real world example for it

Marketing 

As a recommendation system

In online platforms like OTT it provide customers preferences by the users.

Finance 

Fraud detection and stock market prediction 

In any financial transaction it can identify unusual pattern of transactions by which it can detect any fraud case.

Stock markets ups and downs pattern can be detected.

Technology 

Speech and Image recognition

Machine learning provides accuracy in the authentication of speech and image recognition.

Types of machine learning 

Supervised learning 

In this learning, models are levelled on the dataset means algorithm learns between the relationship between input data and output data.

Unsupervised learning 

In this learning algorithm discover the pattern or relationship without any predefined data output.

Reinforcement learning

This learning is based on the error or trial or feedback like robotic control.

Some famous machine learning algorithms are 

  • Linear regression 
  • Decision tree
  • K-Nearest neighbours
#Note-
A machine learning model learns pattern from two types of data training data and testing data.
Machine learning has two key concept- feature and label. Features are the measuring property of the data and levels are targets or output.
There are challenges in machine learning- Bias and privacy concern are two main challenges.

fields.title: What is blockchain technology ?
fields.tags: What is blockchain, what is blockchain technology, blockchain, consensus mechanism, application of blockchain, types of blockchain
fields.body:
Blockchain is a digital distributed ledger or database which is kept in a synchronised form over the network of a computers that make it secure, transparent and immutable.

Blockchain technology is also known as distributed ledger technology(DLT) using decentralization and cryptographic hashing technique.

How it works 

There are two fundamental mechanics of blockchain -blocks and nodes. 

Blocks - Simply blockchain is the chain of blocks in which a block acts as a page of ledger that contain some relevant information. 

Node - Blockchain doesnot have any Central authority.It is a distributed network means many computer(node) connected to the networks and each network having a copy of entire blockchain.

So, each block stores its relevant information in an interconnected blocks and create a data chronology.

Every block creates a unique code known as Hash which is store in it and also store previous block Hash. This makes the security of data.

Data security in Blockchain

Data security is the key feature of blockchain technology because in this if hacker wants to change the information of any block then hash code of block changes automatically and it took too long time for the hacker to change the Hash of every successive block as well as it also required consensus of the network.

 Consensus Mechanism
Blockchain works collaboratively by networks of computer(node) to validate the relative info through consensus mechanism like proof of work.

Types of blockchain 

Blockchains are mainly three types-

Public blockchain

This blockchain is open for everyone and entirely decentralized.

Private blockchain

In this blockchain there are some restricted access on network.

Consortium blockchain

Consortium blockchain has balance between private and public blockchain and govern by pre-selected group of organisation.

Application of blockchain 

  • Supply chain management
  • Transportation 
  • Crime management
  • Fintech 
  • Cryptocurrency(Bitcoin)
  • Real estate management
  • Healthcare
#Note-We can create blockchains for our business or presentation purpose by a specific language.
Blockchain has a smart contract in which data interchange are described in a contract form in the digital format.
There is a famous blockchain Ethereum which can we used by social contract through a specific language Solidity.

fields.title: Ancient Vedic Period (1500BC - 600BC)
fields.tags: What is Vedic period, Vaidik period polity, Vedic period religion, Vedic period society, Vedic periodic economy what is rigvedic period, what is early Vedic period, what is later Vedic period
fields.body:
Vedic Period (1500BC- 600BC) started after the decline of Indus civilization and coming of Aryans. It is still a controversial issue about the origin home of the Aryans. Some scholar believe that Aryans were native to soil of India and others believe that they were migrated from outside (Central Asia). B. G. Tilak said that they were migrated to India from Arctic region.

In Vedic period many literatures were composed.

These are

Vedas (4)- Rigveda,Yajurved,Samved and Atharvaveda.

Brahmanas,Aranyakas,Upanishad(Vedanta)(108)-(oldest Upanishad Vrihadaranyaka).

Literature of Vedic tradition after Vedic Period- 

Sutras(6),Smritis(6),Mahakavyas(2)-Ramayan(Valmiki),Mahabharat(Vedvyas),

Puran (18)-Matsya Purana,Vishnu Purana,Vayu Puran etc.

Vedic Period were divided into two segments

Early Vedic/Rigvedic Period(1500BC-1000BC)

Rigved is the only source of knowledge of rigvedic period.According to rigved a famous war the battle of 10 King (Dasrajan war) were fought for the supremacy over the land on the bank of purushni (Ravi) river in which Sudas(Bharat tribes) emerged victorious.

Polity 

The Kula(family) was the basic unit of society and politics.A group of kula formed gram(village) then vis(clan),Jana(people),Rashtra.The Rashtra was ruled by a king or Rajan which was a hereditary post.The Purohit(priest) was the first ranking officer others are Senani(Army chief), Gramani (village head).

Society 

Rigvedic society was divided into four varnas- Brahmana, kshatriya,vaishya and shudra based on their occupation not hereditary. Widow marriage was allowed they could marry the younger brother of the disease husband(Niyoga). Cow could not be killed.It was a sin(Aghanya).

Religion 

Indira, Agni and Varun were the main deities of Rigvedic Aryans.

Economy 

This vedic people are not familiar with cat and camel.Cows and gold ornaments were used as a barter system in market.

Later Vedic Period(1000BC-600BC)

During this period Aryans settled in whole of the Northern India.Emergence of Janapadas in doab region like Kuru,Panchala and Kashi etc.

Polity 

The monarchy government becomes more elaborate. King did not have any standing army. Judiciary grow,More Civil posts came into function there were- Bhagadadha(collector of taxes),Suta/Sarathi (Royal Charioteer).

Society 

Emergence of varnas divided the society, institution of gotra come into existence,polygamy (having more than one wife) was frequent. Women were prohibited from political activity and their status were declined. In this period Jabala Upnishad given the reference of 4 Ashrams- Brahmacharya,Grihastha,Vanprasth and Sanyas.

Religion 

Prajapati(creator of universe known as Brahma), Vishnu,Rudra were became new prominent Gods.

In this later Vedic period brahmanas sacrifices becomes prominent.There are two varieties of sacrifice

1. Laghuyajanas(for simple household)and

2. Mahayajanas(Royal sacrifices)

Economy 

Land became more valuable then cows. Agriculture began,Advance knowledge of metals tin,silver and iron are acknowledged and Merchants made guilt(Union).

fields.title: What are Synthetic Fibres?
fields.tags: What are synthetic fibres, synthetic fibre, what is Rayon, what is nylon, what is polyester, what is acrylic, properties of synthetic fibres
fields.body:
Natural fibres are obtained from plant or animal.Cotton and jute are the plant natural fibres while, silk and wool are the animal natural fibres.They are made up of organic substances whose smallest units (Monomer) are carbon and hydrogen. Fibres are the combination of monomers known as polymer.

So,synthetic fibres are also a large combination of small unit (monomer) known as polymer and the process is known as polymerization, but it's smallest unit means monomers are chemical raw substances (petrochemical).Using these chemical substances synthetic fibres are prepared in laboratories by the process of polymerization.

There are many types of Synthetic Fibres

Rayon 

Rayon is the most widely useful semi-synthetic fibre because it's property is similar to the silk and cheaper than silk. It is also known as artificial silk.Its fibre is obtained by chemical treatment of wood pulp.

Nylon 

Nylon is a man-made fibre discovered in 1931. It is made from an organic compound. It's fibres are strong,elastic and light.Nylon fibres are much stronger than Steel wire that's why it is used for making parachutes and climbing ropes.

Polyester 

Polyester is also a synthetic fibre which is made up of repeating unit of a chemical substance called Ether. Ethers are obtained from chemicals.Polyesters are suitable for making dress material like terrycotton(Terylene+ Cotton).Terylene and PET(polyethylene terephthalate) are two popular polyesters used in making households articles.

Acrylic

Acrylics is known as synthetic wool which is prepared by synthetic fibre. Since, wool is quite expensive and dependent for availability on animals.So,acrylics are very popular for cheap cost and available in variety of colours.

Properties of Synthetic Fibres

1. Synthetic fibres are not depend either on an agriculture crop(cotton, jute) or on animal  farming(silk,wool).

2. They are more stronger and durable the natural fibres.

3. They are generally cheaper then natural fibre. 

4. They are easy to maintain like folding,washing, ironing and quickly dry up.

#Note-
Synthetic fibres are sticky to the skin and melt easily by heating.Therefore, we should not wear synthetic fibres clothes in kitchen or fireworks.

fields.title: What is end-to-end encryption(E2EE) ?
fields.tags: What is end to end encryption, what is encryption, what is encryption technique, what is symmetric encryption, what is a symmetric encryption, problem of government by end to end encryption
fields.body:
Encryption is a method to safe your data and information from any unauthorised access.

Encryption technique transforms the data into a secret code(unreadable) by algorithm program and this secret code decrypted or deciphered only by authorised recipient.

In this process only authorised party can read this data by converting it back into readable form.

There are two main types of encryption 

 

1. Symmetric Encryption

In this encryption process, a secret key is generated for both encryption and decryption. With the help of encryption algorithm (AES-Advance Encryption System) the data and key is converted into a secret code and transmitted, then authorised receiver use the same key to decrypt the data.

Data + Key -----E----->Secret Code
Secret Code + Key ------D------> Data 

So, a single generated key plays an important role in this process. 

 

2. Asymmetric Encryption

This encryption process generates a pair of key, one is public key and other is a private key. Public key is shared openly and private key is kept secure. Using Encryption algorithm (RSA- Rivest Shamir Adleman) the data and public key is encrypted into secret code and transmitted, then receiver with the help of private key decrypt the secret code by decryption algorithm into readable data.

Data+Public Key ---E--->Secret Code
Secret Code+Private Key ---D--->Data

 

End-to-End Encryption

(E2EE)

End to end encryption is a technique of asymmetric encryption process in which data privacy safeguard is enhanced. E2EE-enabled apps (like WhatsApp and Telegram) give the feature in which only sender and receiver can decrypt the exchange data.

In this process messages get encrypted on the device before being sent and it can only decrypted when data reaches to the authorised party. So this encryption technique gives complete privacy assurance that hackers or not even company can decrypt the data. 

Advantage
In E2EE process data is fully secured from hackers,tempering and cybercriminals.

 

Problem
Now, the government raised a concern over this enabled app for National Security because this E2EE technology does not allow to monitor illegal activity, facing problem to find the origin of fake data circulation and secure terrorist groups to secretly communicate.

fields.title: Powers of Indian Parliament
fields.tags: What are the powers of Indian Parliament, Indian Parliament powers, what are the executive power of parliament, what are the legislative power of parliament, what are the judicial power of parliament
fields.body:
India is a largest democratic country in the world. So, Indian parliament is the parliament of world's largest democracy. As in democracy, there are three main organs of government- Executive Legislature and Judiciary. Parliament is the legislative organ of the government. Since,India has adopted a parliamentary form of Government. So, it has a close relationship between legislature (Parliament) and Executive (Council of ministers).

Indian parliament has two houses- House of the People(Lok Sabha) and Council of States (Rajya Sabha). In Election, the party which has majority in the Lok Sabha form government if the government losses the confidence of the house then the government is collapsed.In this form of government, all ministers are required to be the member of the parliament.

Indian Parliament enjoys three types of powers

Legislative Power

1. The parliament has a power to make laws on the matters included in Union list and Concurrent list given in the seven schedule of the Indian constitution. It can also make laws on the matter of Subject list in case of National Emergency or Presidency's Rule in the state.

2. Article 368 of the Indian Constitution gives the power of the constitutional amendments to the Indian Parliament. Since, during law enactment and amendments bill required the simple majority but in case of Constitution amendment Bill required special majority.

3. The parliament may by law create new states or change the boundaries of the existing States(Article 2,3) and it is not considered an amendment under article 368 (Article 4) means it can do it by simple majority.

4. Article 11 gives the power to the parliament to make laws on the Citizenship.

5. In Article 169, the parliament may by law create or abolish legislative council in a state by simple majority and it is also not considered as an amendment under Article 368.

6. Parliament has the power to approve or disapproved the proclamation of National emergency( in one month) ,financial emergency or presidents rule in different states( in two month).

7. It can cease an ordinance issued by president after the period of six weeks from date of commencement of the session of parliament.

Executive Power 

Union ministers are selected and appointed from amongst the members of parliament.If a person, who is not a member of parliament, appointed as a minister, can be cease to be minister after expired of the period of six month, unless such person become the member of either house of the parliament.

Article 75 says that executive function of parliament is provided to the council of minister and the council of minister shall be collectively responsible to the house of the people.

Lok Sabha controls the executive or Council of ministers and they are accountable to the Lok Sabha because Lok Sabha is the people's representative house.

There are various tools are available in the Lok Sabha to control the Council of ministers 

  • No confidence motion (for entire council of minister) 
  • Censurer motion (for individual minister)
  • Adjournment motion 
  • Calling attention motion 
  • Question hour 
  • Zero hour
Judicial Power

Indian parliament enjoys some Power which is judicial in nature.It has the power to remove some constitutional post holder on the ground of proved Misbehaviour or Incapacity. These are

  • The judges of supreme court and high courts 
  • The chief election commissioner 
  • The comptroller and auditor General 
  • State election commission 

Parliament has also power to remove President of India by motion of impeachment (Article 61).

Both house of the parliament have the power to punish a person who is found guilty or breaching the privilege of house or its member.

Hence, Parliament act as a debateble forum on the policies that have weaknesses and strengths and inform public opinion about them.It is act as a link between the people and the governmentm.

fields.title: What is Shock Wave ?
fields.tags: Shock wave,What is shock wave,how shock wave are forms,breaking sound barriers,shock wave around jet plane,expansion fan,what is expansion fan
fields.body:
Thinking that a jet plane or aeroplane accelerate sound time to time. When the plane reaches supersonic speed mean (faster than speed of sound), it breaks the sound barriers and form shock wave around plane.The sound barriers are too close in this situation, that the gap betweem barriers are  approximately 100 to 500 nanometres.Then we will see that tops of sound barriers are very close and below the barriers of sound will be going to far away form the plane.

But, actually this is not shock wave.In the real, it is condenses droplets of water and tiny ice cystals. When the hot and warm gases exhaust from engine of plane it condenses water and ice because, the gases flow from expansion fan also called Pradtl-Meyer expansion fan. The temperature, static pressure and density decreases and the temperture of altitude are very low,this is one of the reason behind this.Therefore,we see the breaking Sound barriers not a   shock waves.This is droplet of water and tiny ice crystyal around jet plane at super sonic speed.

Expansion fan

An expansion fan, or Prandtl-Meyer expansion fan  is a phenomenon in supersonic flow where the flow accelerates as it turns around a corner that makes it expand outward. Here are the basic concepts:

  1. Supersonic flow: This is when flow speed in faster than speed of sound.
  2. Expansion Waves: When supersonic flow encounters a convex corner or diverging surface, it spreads out and accelerates, creating a series of small waves called expansion waves.

  3. Flow Characteristics:

  • Speed: The flow speed(Mach numabers are increses)
  • Pressure and Temperature: Both decrease as the flow expands.
  • Direction: The flow changes direction smoothly around the corner.

Applications

Expansion fans are important in the design of supersonic aircraft and rockets, helping to manage and optimize the flow characteristics for better performance and stability.

In summar season, an expansion fan is a pattern of waves that form when supersonic flow expands and accelerates around a convex corner, resulting in increased speed and decreased pressure and temperature.

 

The Shock waves are actually form when a object or thing is travel faster than speed of light in medimedium.

 

In,this picture the electron travel faster than speed of light in water

fields.title: Human Evolution
fields.tags: What is human evolution, who is Hominins, who was homo erectus, who was austroalopithus, who was homo neanderthal, who was homo sapien
fields.body:
Human Evolution is the process of change of human being, which developed on the earth from the originated point to till now.

Human Evolution started nearly seven million years ago. It is assumed that, in this time human genealogy separated from Chimpanzees, Alps and Monkeys because this Pleistocene period which was an ice age, insisted these animals to get down on the earth from trees. This developed twenty different types of human species or Hominins, in which only few was servived by natural selection.

There are many stages of human evolution but three primary groups are discussed here

1. Early Hominins 

2. Austroalopithus 

3. Homo Genus

Hominins

(7 million years ago)

Hominins are the early stage of human species existed near the seven millions year ago. With passing of time they evolved and change their physical and mental appearance into Sahenlanthropus (6 millions years ago), Ardipithecus (5 million years ago) and then Austroalopithus.

Austroalopithus

( 5 million BC - 3 million BC)

They are early ancestor of humans because they changed their physical activity from 4 legs to use of 2 free hands and but walk in tilted mode.They started hunting by sharp stone equipment.

It's archaeological remains found in Africa only. A female skeleton was obtained from Africa name Lucy is known as "mother of man".

Homo Genus

Homo Genus appeared in 3 millions years ago and it also have a different stages of evolution.

1. Homo Erectus

( 3 million BC - 1 million BC)

This stage of human species walked firstly on their two legs with erected posture. It's archaeological remains found in different continent Asia, Europe and Africa. In India homo erectus remains found at Hathnora village of Hoshangabad district Maghya Pradesh. There was the first who discovered fire. Evolution changes their physical appearance and increased their mental ability by which two different homo species developed -

2. Homo Neanderthal

(1 million BC - 40,000 BC)

Since, they are curious like a modern human they spread to all over the world, started hunting in teamwork and communicate through a language to co-ordinate. But nearly 40,000 to 30,000 BC Homo Neanderthal species exticted, this mysteries is unknown and the research is in continue.

3. Homo Sapiens

(40,000 BC -10,000 BC)

Homo Sapiens remains the last and the latest ancestor of modern man but there survivor was continue again coming of ice age era and they faced it by the ancestor discovery of fire. After due to shortage of food the learn the method of agriculture.

fields.title: What is Artificial Intelligence?
fields.tags: What is artificial intelligence, how it is rised, what are the types of AI, what are the applications of artificial intelligence what are the ethical concern of artificial intelligence
fields.body:
Artificial intelligence is a modern branch of computer science that deals with the creation and development of algorithms and software to perform a specific task which required human intelligence like learning, reasoning, problem solving, language understanding and perception.

Artificial intelligence has become a new or modern feature of a machine or computer system that has capability to replicate as a intelligent human behaviour. 

Today, the development of different algorithms that allow the machine or computer system to perform extraordinary functions such as learning from experience(machine learning), recognizing patterns, understanding natural language etc.

Rise of Artificial Intelligence 

Artificial intelligence begin with the dream of creating mechanisms that could mimic human intelligence. John MaCarthy, a stanford University researchers coind this Artificial Intelligence term firstly.He is also known as father of AI.

Artificial intelligence can we categorised generally into two section 

1.Narrow AI 

This AI is design and trained for a specific task for narrow range. It is also a week AI.

Ex- Siri,Alexa, google search etc

2. General AI 

General AI would have the ability to perform any intellectual task that a human can.

Artificial intelligence has emerged as a transformative field that reshaping our interaction with the world through Machine learning and Data analytics technologies.

Application of Artificial Intelligence 

  • Finance 
  • Healthcare 
  • Transportation 
  • Entertainment etc.

Benefits of AI 

  • Efficiency 
  • Accuracy
  • 24 * 7 Availability
  •  Innovation

Ethical risk of artificial intelligence 

1. Privacy and Security 

AI often involves in the processing of large data. Inadequate protection of these data can lead to privacy breach and malicious attack lead to security breach and misuse.

2. Job displacement 

3. Bias or fairness

If the training data used to develop AI algorithm, contains bias then AI may learn and perpetuate those bias and lead to unfair or discriminatory outcomes.

4. Transparency 

It is important for user and stakeholder to have transparency that how AI system makes decision and how it works.

5. Ethical decision making 

Human judgement with moral reasoning are the complex situation that AI system may struggle with ethical decision making.

fields.title: What is Fiscal Federalism ?
fields.tags: What is fiscal federalism, what are the principle of fiscal federalism, what is revenue allocation, what is grant, what is fiscal autonomy, what is fiscal accountability, relation between India and US federation, what is finance commission, niti aayog
fields.body:
Fiscal Federalism is the financial relation amongst different layers of government (federal, state and local) in a federal system.

It addresses the allocation of resources and responsibilities among these different layers of government. 

There are two types of government in the world.
1. Unitary Government and
2. Federal Government

 

Federation is derived from a Latin word 'foedus' means treaty or agreement. So, federation is a political system which is formed through a treaty or agreement between the various units.

Principals of Fiscal Federalism

1. Efficiency 

It ensures that resources of state are used in a way that maximize the benefit to society. 

2. Equity 

In fiscal federalism, a fair distribution of resources and services should be achieved across different region and population.

3. Stability 

It should prevent fiscal imbalance by implementing fiscal policy to manage economic fluctuations.

Revenue allocation (tax and grant), Expenditure responsibility and Fiscal autonomy & Accountability are the key features of fiscal federalism.

Revenue Allocation is a distribution of taxes among federal, state and local government in which different levels may have distinct taxes.
Grand is a type of fund transfer from higher level of government to lower level to support specific project or budget.
Fiscal Autonomy is the freedom to all lower governments to be independent for revenue rising powers and spending authority.
Fiscal Accountability is the mechanism to ensure that government are accountable to the citizens for their financial decision and performance.

Difference between India and USA Federalism 

India and USA are the best example of federal countries. USA federalism represents the idea of 'coming together' that describe an indestructible Union with indestructible States while Indian federalism opposite it represents the idea of 'holding together' that describes an indestructible Union with destructible States.

Indian Federalism 

India follows the process and procedure of fiscal federalism in which the annual budgetary process of both the centre and the state government independently exercise and must pass through Parliament or state legislature.

Finance Commission
Article 280 of the Indian Constitution deals with the finance commission, it is a constitutional body with power and responsibility of devolution of resources between the centre and the state government.

 

NITI Ayog
The planning commission which was also a part of fiscal federation was dismantled and established a National Institute of Transforming India(NITI Ayog) on January 1 2015. It is a thing tank of Indian government, work more efficiently on the principle of cooperative federalism.
